AGI - "We're dealing with Putin and I think it's going reasonably well. It is a very complex situation, a terrible war. I think Putin> will accept the ceasefire. We'll know a little more on Monday, let's hope it's okay." This was said by US President Donald Trump> in a video interview with the head of 'Full Measure' of which an anticipation was published on YouTube.&nbsp;
Pressing the Russian President to " finally sit at the table" and "stop barbarian attacks to Ukraine" is, according to the British press, the goal of the British Prime Minister Keir Starmer> who convened the meeting of 25 world leaders > to define the general lines of a coalition of countries willing to "support a just and lasting peace" in Ukraine.&nbsp; The 'coalition of the willing' agreed in order to increase the pressure on Russia. "We will not stand still watching Putin," Starmer said, "increasing pressure to weaken Putin" also with an increase in sanctions.
"The total contempt of the Kremlin for the proposal to cease the fire of President Trump only demonstrates that Putin does not take seriously peace," continued Starmer.&nbsp;
Macron, after the meeting of the 'coalition of the voluntarians, accused Russia of tracing on the proposal of truce set up in Gedda between the United States and Ukraine. Moscow "does not give the impression of sincerely wanting peace," he explained. Russia "does not respond to the proposal of the United States and Ukraine" and indeed "is intensifying the fights, he recalled, "Russian President Vladimir&nbsp;Putin&nbsp;" he wanted to get everything and then negotiate". But that can't work. "If we want peace, Russia must respond clearly and that the pressure to obtain the ceasefire is clear, along with the United States," he warned.&nbsp;
In words Vladimir Putin says he wants peace, but in fact he is taking time, he added Starmer. "We welcomed the efforts of President Trump, President Zelensky and their team to ensure the extraordinary breakthrough on the peace agreement in Gedda this week," he told journalists. The Ukrainian leader accepted "the United States proposal for an immediate and unconditional ceasefire of 30 days, subject to Russia's agreement". So "we have agreed that now the ball is in the field of Russia and that President Putin must demonstrate that he is seriously intent on peace and sign a ceasefire under conditions," he insisted. "The hesitations and delays of the Kremlin on the proposal of ceasefire of President Trump and the continuous barbaric attacks of Russia against Ukraine are in total contrast with the desire for peace declared by President Putin," said the British prime minister.
Starmer&nbsp; he then announced that the 'coalition of the willful' is ready to move from political discussion to action. "Let's move to the operational phase," he said after the videoconference on Saturday.> "Our military meets Thursday to implement a robust plan," he announced at the press conference. "The world needs action, not empty words and conditions. So my message is clear, sooner or later Putin will have to sit at the table," he continues. "It's time to give us something to do for the result we all want: the end of the killings, and a just lasting peace", he continued.&nbsp;Starmer>&nbsp; he reiterated that the coalition of the volenterants is determined to engage directly on the ground. "We will strengthen the defence and the Ukrainian armed forces and we will be ready to deploy as a 'coalition of willing' in the event of a peace agreement, to help protect Ukraine on earth, at sea and in the heavens," he said. "In case of ceasefire, we stressed the need for strong monitoring provisions, to ensure that any violation is identified and denounced," he continued.
For the President of the European Commission, Ursula von der Leyen>, la&nbsp;Russia "must prove to support a ceasefire that leads to a just and lasting peace". &nbsp;
<h2>Melons: "With Ue and Usa for guarantees in Kiev. No to send Italian soldiers"</h2>
The President of the Council, Giorgia Meloni, attended the meeting in video conferencing organized by the Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, Keir Starmer, on the commitment to a just and lasting peace, which assures the future sovereignty and security of Ukraine, reads in a note of Palazzo Chigi. The President of the Council confirmed that Italy intends to continue working with European and Western partners and with the United States for the definition of credible and effective security guarantees, reasserting that national participation in any military force on the ground is not envisaged.&nbsp;
In the evening, the premier&nbsp; had a telephone conversation with the Crown Prince and Prime Minister of Saudi Arabia, Mohamed bin Salman at Saud.> "In light of the positive outcome of the talks held in Gedda at the beginning of the week and following the videoconference this morning convened by Prime Minister Starmer, the two leaders - read in a note of Palazzo Chigi - have in particular discussed the ongoing initiatives and the shared commitment for a just and lasting peace in Ukraine. Finally, the interview allowed an exchange of views on recent developments in the Middle East region.' &nbsp;
<h2>Zelensky, no encirclement of our
Our forces continue in some areas of the Kursk region. Units perform tasks exactly as required. Thanks to Ukrainian forces in Kursk, a significant number of Russian troops were withdrawn from other directions. Our troops continue to contain Russian and North Korean groups in Kursk. There is no encirclement of our troops," writes Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky on Telegram. "We also see areas along our eastern border with Ukraine where the Russian army is strengthening its forces. This indicates the will to strike our Sumy region. We understand and contrast it. I would like all partners to understand exactly what Putin is planning, what he is preparing for and what exactly he will ignore." "The increase in Russian forces indicates that Moscow intends to continue to ignore diplomacy. The prolonged war of Russia is evident. We are ready to provide our partners with all the real information on the situation at the front, in the Kursk region and along the border." &nbsp;
<h2>Cremlin, EU leaders as dogs at the foot of Trump</h2>
"As provided by President Vladimir Putin, European leaders under Trump behave like dogs at the foot of their master." This was said by the diplomatic adviser of the Kremlin, Yuri Ushakov, as reported by Ria Novosti.&nbsp; The councilman recalled the words of the Russian president according to which Trump, with his character, will quickly restore the order and European leaders "will put themselves at the foot of the master and will nervously squander". "Putin described them as loving dogs at the foot of their master, well, it's more or less what's going on now," Ushakov said.&nbsp;
<div </div
<h2> Attacks continued
Russian air defence systems have intercepted and destroyed 126 Ukrainian drones > which flew over Russian regions at night. The Russian Defense Ministry reported this, according to the Tass website. "In the last night, air defense systems in service destroyed and intercepted 126 Ukrainian drones: 64 on the territory of the Volgograd region, 38 on the territory of the Voronezh region, 14 on the territory of the Belgorod region, seven on the territory of the Bryansk region, two on the territory of the Rostov region and one on the territory of the Kursk region," said the dicastery.&nbsp;
The Ukrainian military air force announced it had destroyed 130 drones launched by Russia> during night attacks. The Ukrainians also denounced an attack with drones in Odessa caused serious damage, a fire and wounded. Dtek energy plants, the main private energy supplier of Ukraine, in the Dnipropetrovsk and Odessa regions, have also been "meaningly" damaged. Still, two people were killed and 18 others were wounded in the Kherson Oblast, >where &nbsp;> Russians targeted critical infrastructure, residential areas of settlements in the region, also damaging seven skyscrapers and 27 houses.<br> &nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2>Macron, "It is not up to Moscow to accept allied forces" &nbsp;</h2>
The French President, Emmanuel Macron, stated in an interview published by several regional newspapers that Russia is not required to "accept or refuse" the sending of "Allied Forces" in Ukraine >se Kiev requested it to ensure a possible peace agreement. In the conversation published online by La Voix du Nord, Ouest-France and Le Parisien, the French president assured that for the moment he has no intention of "interfering" in the dialogue between the United States and Russia. On the other hand, "from the moment we enter into this phase of ceasefire" proposed by Washington and Kiev, underlined Macron, will be necessary "direct exchanges" with his Russian counterpart Vladimir&nbsp;Putin&nbsp;" and among the French and Russian negotiators to clarify this agenda" on the security guarantees to provide to Ukraine.

