The Russian authorities, writes the Moscow Times, seem irritated by the efforts of the British Prime Minister, Keir Starmer, to ensure European support for Ukraine, at a time when the new American administration manifests reluctance. Starmer has set up a 'coalition of willingness' of countries willing to ally to continue to provide military aid to Kiev and protect it from further Russian aggression in the event of a peace agreement, also through the sending of troops. A hypothesis against which the Kremlin was forced, warning that this would open a "direct comparison" with Moscow.
Starmer and his national security advisor Jonathan Powell also made great efforts to reconcile Kiev with Washington and negotiate a ceasefire of 30 days with the aim of putting Moscow to the corner. Foreign Minister, Serghei Lavrov>, attacked Starmer claiming that he wants escalation. For Russian intelligence abroad (Svr), London considers a threat to its interests the way in which dialogue between the United States and Russia proceeds. On Monday, secret services (Fsb) accused of espionage and expelled two British citizens stationed at the embassy in Moscow. "It is clear that Russia is trying to push the British embassy towards closure," said the Foreign Office in a note.&nbsp;
